sunglasses at a stand.

918
01:07:55,113 --> 01:07:57,783
He had a couple funny lines,
but they got cut.

919
01:07:57,950 --> 01:08:02,371
One of his lines was,
"Yeah, they use these in X-Men."

920
01:08:03,538 --> 01:08:07,125
- There's your cameo.
- I ran by in front of the kid.

921
01:08:07,292 --> 01:08:11,964
Shot at the very end of production.

922
01:08:12,172 --> 01:08:16,969
There was a case of the glider
coming back to the Goblin...

923
01:08:17,177 --> 01:08:22,766
...waiting on him for when he needs
to jump back on, like a cowboy's horse.

924
01:08:25,269 --> 01:08:30,315
A lot of these ground shots of Goblin
we used as lighting reference...

925
01:08:30,524 --> 01:08:34,653
...when we were developing our Goblin
CG model, and its lighting model.

926
01:08:34,820 --> 01:08:36,154
There he is.

927
01:08:36,321 --> 01:08:40,075
This was shot by
Pedram Goshtasbpour...

928
01:08:41,827 --> 01:08:46,498
It cuts together with live action,
goes back and forth between the two.

929
01:08:49,126 --> 01:08:52,170
Watch Goblin spin out.

930
01:08:53,505 --> 01:08:57,301
- He stalled.
- Kicking off a wave on a surfboard.

931
01:09:00,470 --> 01:09:06,810
Interestingly, the people in the street
are made of digital characters...

932
01:09:07,019 --> 01:09:08,979
...generated in the computer...

933
01:09:09,187 --> 01:09:11,606
...people from Downey,
who were shot...

934
01:09:11,815 --> 01:09:14,693
I think we had 5000 people one day.

935
01:09:14,901 --> 01:09:18,322
Another day we had 1000,
then it got down to 250.

936
01:09:18,488 --> 01:09:20,032
People got tired of coming.

937
01:09:20,240 --> 01:09:23,869
And the crowds in the streets
are all made up...

938
01:09:25,579 --> 01:09:29,541
...of separate pieces
that are all sewn together...

939
01:09:29,750 --> 01:09:35,797
...to create much more scope
than we actually had to photograph.

940
01:09:35,964 --> 01:09:40,719
This is Peter Nofz's sequence,
as a CG supervisor.

941
01:09:40,886 --> 01:09:45,682
He coordinated the set up of a bunch
of these different systems...

942
01:09:45,891 --> 01:09:49,311
...including our crowd system
and the character setup.

943
01:09:49,519 --> 01:09:51,813
He got a taste of every pipeline.

944
01:09:51,980 --> 01:09:55,776
Our building pipeline,
our painted tile pipeline.

945
01:09:55,942 --> 01:10:00,364
We stitched together photography
that John shot in New York.

946
01:10:00,530 --> 01:10:01,698
It came together.

947
01:10:01,865 --> 01:10:08,622
Just for the sense of description,
when Scott talks about a pipeline...

948
01:10:08,789 --> 01:10:15,003
...it's the process characters and
environments go through to be finished.

949
01:10:15,170 --> 01:10:19,508
Once principle photography is done,
if that's a component of a shot...

950
01:10:19,674 --> 01:10:24,137
...let's say a background plate,
in the case of this New York piece...

951
01:10:24,304 --> 01:10:27,474
...then all of the pieces
begin to come together.

952
01:10:27,641 --> 01:10:32,521
Those pieces may take five weeks
to assemble, or a week to assemble.

953
01:10:32,687 --> 01:10:35,732
We call the length of time
that it takes...

954
01:10:35,941 --> 01:10:41,613
...to go from the beginning components
to its completion a "pipeline."

955
01:10:41,822 --> 01:10:46,910
In some cases the pipeline
is tied to a character.

956
01:10:47,077 --> 01:10:50,789
In other cases, it's tied
to the complexity of the shot.

957
01:10:50,956 --> 01:10:55,836
The last shot in the movie
took six months, I believe.

958
01:10:56,002 --> 01:11:00,674
- Yeah, six to eight months.
- That's not a pure pipeline...

959
01:11:00,841 --> 01:11:04,428
...but it gives you a sense
of how long it takes.

960
01:11:04,594 --> 01:11:10,100
We had to decide what we were actually
going to do fairly early on...

961
01:11:10,267 --> 01:11:15,230
...to get the shots done by the time
the film was in the theatres.

962
01:11:18,900 --> 01:11:22,195
By the time we got
into really finishing...

963
01:11:22,362 --> 01:11:25,740
...or getting close to finishing
the last swing shot...

964
01:11:25,907 --> 01:11:29,286
...everybody wanted to do
more shots like it.

965
01:11:29,453 --> 01:11:33,582
We just knew we didn't have the time
in the schedule to do more.

966
01:11:33,748 --> 01:11:35,542
Well, you use every moment.

967
01:11:35,709 --> 01:11:38,795
I have yet to work on a movie
where we said:

968
01:11:38,962 --> 01:11:41,465
"We're done. We'll take the week off."

969
01:11:41,673 --> 01:11:46,928
You always work until,
as Sam said for this movie...

970
01:11:47,095 --> 01:11:50,682
...I believe he's quoting someone
else but he says:

971
01:11:50,891 --> 01:11:54,603
"They will pry the film
from his cold, dead hands."

972
01:11:54,853 --> 01:11:58,690
That's pretty much the way
these movies always are.

973
01:11:58,857 --> 01:12:04,613
The whole process,
from script to storyboard artists...

974
01:12:04,779 --> 01:12:07,115
...to Sam, and then over to us...

975
01:12:07,282 --> 01:12:12,037
...then going through you, John,
then filtering through other people.

976
01:12:12,204 --> 01:12:17,667
Going from me to the animators, and
then back in the other direction again.

977
01:12:17,834 --> 01:12:21,046
It goes back and forth
through this hierarchy...

978
01:12:21,213 --> 01:12:25,675
...and you arrive at something
until Sam finally agrees upon it.

979
01:12:25,842 --> 01:12:29,513
But everybody has their input
into these things.

980
01:12:29,679 --> 01:12:33,808
And different people input
on many different things.

981
01:12:33,975 --> 01:12:37,020
The lighter can comment
about the animation.

982
01:12:37,229 --> 01:12:41,775
An animator might comment
about the lighting.

983
01:12:42,317 --> 01:12:43,777
It works a little...

984
01:12:43,944 --> 01:12:47,072
- Is that a sore spot?
- No. Not at all.

985
01:12:47,239 --> 01:12:52,452
Anthony and I always argue
a little bit in jest, in dailies.

986
01:12:52,619 --> 01:12:56,790
- But we won't do that now.
- Oh, I'll miss it.

987
01:12:56,998 --> 01:13:01,878
I was gonna say, the pre-visualization
that Anthony was talking about...

988
01:13:02,045 --> 01:13:07,425
...it's different for live-action shots
and an all-CG shot.

989
01:13:07,592 --> 01:13:12,931
For live-action photography,
a lot of it was used to hash out...

990
01:13:13,098 --> 01:13:17,894
...where the camera should be
and what lens would be used...

991
01:13:18,061 --> 01:13:21,398
...and to block out
for the day of the shooting.

992
01:13:21,565 --> 01:13:27,946
In the case of all-CG shots,
it was actually much easier, in a way.

993
01:13:28,113 --> 01:13:32,492
The animators were really blocking out
the shot in that case.

994
01:13:32,659 --> 01:13:37,122
It just went from pre-vis
to finishing animation stages...

995
01:13:37,289 --> 01:13:43,211
...straight into lighting without a
photography section in that path.

996
01:13:43,378 --> 01:13:46,131
We talked about pre-visualization...

997
01:13:46,506 --> 01:13:50,510
...which is the geometry of a set
or a location...

998
01:13:50,677 --> 01:13:53,680
...and simple geometry
of the characters...

999
01:13:53,847 --> 01:13:58,184
...with a virtual camera that can be
positioned to create shots.

1000
01:13:58,351 --> 01:14:03,982
We did pre-visualization on shots that
were live-action pieces, as well...

1001
01:14:04,149 --> 01:14:08,320
...so that when we showed up on-stage
to do the photography...

1002
01:14:08,486 --> 01:14:12,449
...we could tell the director of
photography the focal lengths...

1003
01:14:12,616 --> 01:14:16,745
...and the distance from the camera
to the subject.

1004
01:14:16,911 --> 01:14:23,001
That was a place to begin.
Pre-visualization isn't cast in stone.

1005
01:14:23,209 --> 01:14:26,504
It's always, again, a living document.

1006
01:14:26,713 --> 01:14:29,716
But it gave everyone
an exhibit to work with...

1007
01:14:30,258 --> 01:14:33,803
...to determine the needs of a shot
on a given day.

1008
01:14:33,970 --> 01:14:38,975
It makes you more efficient.
You put more of your money on screen...

1009
01:14:39,184 --> 01:14:44,564
...instead of putting the money into
doing fix-its or changing your mind.

1010
01:14:44,773 --> 01:14:46,775
Pre-visualization was good.

1011
01:14:46,941 --> 01:14:52,906
John Schmidt was great about working
out those things for shoot days.

1012
01:14:53,114 --> 01:14:55,867
He also made printouts for them.

1013
01:14:56,076 --> 01:15:00,330
He went through a ream of paper
making printouts used for shooting.

1014
01:15:00,497 --> 01:15:03,625
Here comes the Goblin.

1015
01:15:07,504 --> 01:15:11,383
We worked with the mechanical guys
and the stunts guys.

1016
01:15:11,549 --> 01:15:15,095
In many cases, the Goblin was there
on a practical glider.

1017
01:15:15,553 --> 01:15:21,059
Sometimes it was Willem on the glider,
sometimes it was a stuntperson.

1018
01:15:21,559 --> 01:15:24,896
We had to communicate
on an ongoing basis.

1019
01:15:25,313 --> 01:15:30,360
We used the pre-visualization as the
exhibit that we discussed together.

1020
01:15:30,527 --> 01:15:35,031
It allowed us to bring the proper tools
for the day's photography...

1021
01:15:35,198 --> 01:15:39,703
...as well as the postproduction work
that had to be done in visual effects.

1022
01:15:40,245 --> 01:15:42,455
Another shot by Koji Morihiro...

1023
01:15:42,622 --> 01:15:48,545
...the guy who actually made the set up
for Spider-Man animation.

1024
01:15:48,712 --> 01:15:50,630
Jeff Stern lit that shot.

1025
01:15:50,797 --> 01:15:54,884
When I saw that lighting,
it was such a nice golden-hour look.

1026
01:15:55,051 --> 01:15:58,638
It influenced how we ended up
on that sequence.

1027
01:15:58,805 --> 01:16:02,142
This is a great sequence
to get a feeling...

1028
01:16:02,308 --> 01:16:06,438
...for the psychotic behavior
that Goblin has...

1029
01:16:06,604 --> 01:16:08,732
...and what I looked to...

1030
01:16:08,898 --> 01:16:13,778
...to give different facets of
his behavior in the performance.

1031
01:16:13,987 --> 01:16:16,865
Well, to each his own.

1032
01:16:17,031 --> 01:16:19,993
I chose my path,
you chose the way of the hero.

1033
01:16:24,539 --> 01:16:28,209
This was also the sequence
shot on-stage...

1034
01:16:28,376 --> 01:16:33,506
...and we decided that the backing
didn't have the right contrast level.

1035
01:16:33,673 --> 01:16:38,052
As a post process, we did some
adjustments on the background.

1036
01:16:38,219 --> 01:16:40,096
Put some steam in.

1037
01:16:40,305 --> 01:16:44,184
The other interesting thing,
because of dialogue changes...

1038
01:16:44,350 --> 01:16:48,438
...we obscured the Goblin's mouth
in some of these shots...

1039
01:16:48,605 --> 01:16:51,775
...so the lip-synch wouldn't be off.

1040
01:16:52,358 --> 01:16:55,820
We did a lot of editorial tinkering
with this shot...

1041
01:16:55,987 --> 01:16:59,866
...during the process of making it.

1042
01:17:01,117 --> 01:17:05,997
We went through a lot of different
versions of his performance in this.

1043
01:17:06,164 --> 01:17:10,126
When the glider comes in,
he jumps on it and flies away.

1044
01:17:10,293 --> 01:17:15,256
In his speech, we tried to get across
in his body what Sam wanted him to say.

1045
01:17:15,423 --> 01:17:17,592
We had different versions.

1046
01:17:17,759 --> 01:17:21,846
One time, we were repeating
what he was doing to his head.

1047
01:17:22,388 --> 01:17:27,811
There's something coming up where
he puts his fingers to his head.

1048
01:17:27,977 --> 01:17:29,729
Well, that's cut out.

1049
01:17:29,896 --> 01:17:36,110
But he flies away, and gives
this Shakespearean gesture to him.

1050
01:17:41,157 --> 01:17:46,246
For characters, the actors,
Willem Dafoe and Tobey Maguire...

1051
01:17:46,412 --> 01:17:49,582
...one who's very still,
one who's animated...

1052
01:17:49,749 --> 01:17:53,169
...once we put the costumes on...

1053
01:17:53,336 --> 01:17:59,259
...the somewhat melodramatic motions
become totally acceptable.

1054
01:17:59,467 --> 01:18:05,056
You don't balk at them, because they
replace the business of the guy's face.

1055
01:18:05,223 --> 01:18:09,811
It's very interesting that some of the
motions and positions...

1056
01:18:10,019 --> 01:18:14,732
...that the characters get into
when they're masked seem extreme...

1057
01:18:14,899 --> 01:18:18,611
...but don't seem extreme
in the context of the story.

1058
01:18:18,778 --> 01:18:20,280
So how'd it go?

1059
01:18:22,448 --> 01:18:24,450
They said I needed acting lessons.

1060
01:18:24,701 --> 01:18:27,328
A soap opera told me
I needed acting lessons.

1061
01:18:27,537 --> 01:18:32,792
There's a lot of little wire removal
and some composite shots...

1062
01:18:33,001 --> 01:18:36,379
...Imageworks didn't do.
We worked with vendors.

1063
01:18:36,629 --> 01:18:40,091
CIS, Post Logic, Digiscope
did a lot of the work...

1064
01:18:40,300 --> 01:18:43,011
...coming up in the next
rain sequence.

1065
01:18:43,177 --> 01:18:46,472
What's interesting
about contemporary filmmaking...

1066
01:18:46,639 --> 01:18:50,810
...is it used to be you couldn't
remove wires or posts.

1067
01:18:51,019 --> 01:18:55,940
So production had to be very careful
about what they put into a scene.

1068
01:18:56,149 --> 01:19:01,613
Although, I'd like to say this
production wasn't bad that way.

1069
01:19:01,863 --> 01:19:07,785
On films I've worked on, they've left
the food truck in the background.

1070
01:19:07,952 --> 01:19:10,997
Because it was quicker
to shoot the scene...

1071
01:19:11,205 --> 01:19:14,500
...and have the truck
removed in postproduction.

1072
01:19:14,751 --> 01:19:19,714
And the whole business of wires now,
and posts to support people...

1073
01:19:19,923 --> 01:19:26,012
...to make them fly and do other things
is rampant. Every other shot...

1074
01:19:26,262 --> 01:19:28,473
...in action sequences...

1075
01:19:28,681 --> 01:19:32,644
...often times have support rods,
or tubes...

1076
01:19:32,894 --> 01:19:38,983
...or cranes, or people's hands, that
you end up going back to paint out.

1077
01:19:39,233 --> 01:19:44,238
It's one of the things digital imagery
has provided to the filmmakers.

1078
01:19:44,405 --> 01:19:48,409
You can take eyes from one take
and a mouth from another...

1079
01:19:48,576 --> 01:19:52,580
...and paint them together
to make another shot.

1080
01:19:53,706 --> 01:19:57,126
Pixel Magic was our
other vendor, I forgot to mention.

1081
01:19:57,293 --> 01:20:01,089
Now it doesn't necessarily mean
that you should do that.

1082
01:20:01,965 --> 01:20:05,051
We had many
wire removal and fix it shots...

1083
01:20:05,259 --> 01:20:10,264
...they all just blend together.
I can't remember where they all are.

1084
01:20:26,030 --> 01:20:29,200
Tobey's fighting style
is not martial arts.

1085
01:20:29,409 --> 01:20:34,330
It's a cross, as Anthony was calling
it, between human and superhuman.

1086
01:20:34,539 --> 01:20:38,960
He throws conventional boxing-type
punches, but he also uses...

1087
01:20:39,210 --> 01:20:41,504
...almost Judo-type moves.

1088
01:20:41,754 --> 01:20:46,801
It's kind of an interesting mix
of a collage of fighting styles...

1089
01:20:47,010 --> 01:20:52,306
...which, I think, gives him
a personality all his own.

1090
01:20:52,515 --> 01:20:56,310
I love the shot in that sequence
where he's all wet.

1091
01:20:56,561 --> 01:21:01,149
It's just so unmotivated if you look
at this shot out of context.

1092
01:21:01,357 --> 01:21:04,068
I felt sorry for Tobey in this shot.

1093
01:21:04,277 --> 01:21:07,947
Because I was there
when they shot it...

1094
01:21:08,156 --> 01:21:14,245
...it's difficult for me to see it as
romantic. His sinuses were full of water.

1095
01:21:14,412 --> 01:21:20,043
He was breathing out of his mouth,
through the wet fabric.

1096
01:21:52,658 --> 01:21:56,245
Boy, that spider web
does some interesting stuff.

1097
01:21:56,496 --> 01:21:59,457
- You just press a button...
- And up you go.

1098
01:21:59,707 --> 01:22:03,419
In those shots, even though
you don't see anything...

1099
01:22:03,669 --> 01:22:08,841
...we've done a little extra movement
around and overriding post move...

1100
01:22:09,092 --> 01:22:13,012
...to just reframe or add extra
motion into those shots.

1101
01:22:13,221 --> 01:22:17,225
And there, this is kind
of the first of our daytime...

1102
01:22:17,433 --> 01:22:20,770
...CG buildings in the
background of some shots.

1103
01:22:20,937 --> 01:22:23,856
Except for Times Square.

1104
01:22:24,023 --> 01:22:28,820
Nice work on the webs where they
waft in the wind after he goes...

1105
01:22:28,986 --> 01:22:31,364
...to get back into the window.

1106
01:22:32,698 --> 01:22:37,370
That shot came together pretty fast
at the end of the show.

1107
01:22:38,121 --> 01:22:41,749
That was a kind of last minute
pull-together shot.

1108
01:22:53,010 --> 01:22:58,182
Okay, this fire sequence contains
components shot in New York.

1109
01:22:58,391 --> 01:23:02,812
This piece, for instance,
is located in New York, as is that.

1110
01:23:03,020 --> 01:23:05,606
Once we go inside, we're on a set...

1111
01:23:05,815 --> 01:23:09,443
...that was built once
in a parking lot in Downey...

1112
01:23:09,652 --> 01:23:14,490
...then again, to shoot subsequent
components of the shot...

1113
01:23:14,657 --> 01:23:18,286
...in a parking lot in Culver City.

1114
01:23:18,494 --> 01:23:20,997
It all goes together very nicely.

1115
01:23:21,205 --> 01:23:27,461
This is an example of integrating this
character seamlessly into a scene.

1116
01:23:27,712 --> 01:23:33,092
I think this is a terrific shot
that is in this sequence...

1117
01:23:33,301 --> 01:23:35,011
...which we'll point out.

1118
01:23:35,219 --> 01:23:39,682
It was a great transition
between real and digital actors.

1119
01:23:39,891 --> 01:23:43,853
That was a great shot by Ken Morris,
coming in the window.

1120
01:23:44,061 --> 01:23:49,400
That web, animated by Todd Boyce, was
a web that Sam kept coming back to...

1121
01:23:49,650 --> 01:23:54,155
...as a reference of a floating web
where it wafted into the air.

1122
01:23:54,363 --> 01:23:59,160
He liked that quality. We tried
to get that in some other shots.

1123
01:24:01,204 --> 01:24:07,835
The actors were actually in this set
as it was on fire, wearing Lycra...

1124
01:24:08,044 --> 01:24:14,258
...which is flammable. You can imagine
how excited they were about that.

1125
01:24:14,467 --> 01:24:19,388
I don't know whether Willem talked
about this or Tobey...

1126
01:24:19,597 --> 01:24:24,435
...but it was quite hot on that set.
If you were gonna be on the set...

1127
01:24:24,685 --> 01:24:29,398
...you wore a complete firefighters'
uniform, including a respirator.

1128
01:24:29,607 --> 01:24:33,361
This is Spencer Cook
in a really beautiful shot...

1129
01:24:33,611 --> 01:24:38,616
...where all the elements come together
very well. People thought this...

1130
01:24:38,783 --> 01:24:40,284
...was a real actor.

1131
01:24:40,451 --> 01:24:45,164
Greg Anderson did a great job lighting
that and Greg Derochie...

1132
01:24:45,331 --> 01:24:47,124
...compositing it.

1133
01:24:47,333 --> 01:24:52,129
Jeff Lin doing this work,
Torn Gurney doing this work.

1134
01:24:52,838 --> 01:24:55,549
Razorbats exploding.

1135
01:24:55,883 --> 01:24:59,971
I thought it was a very well
choreographed sequence too.

1136
01:25:04,892 --> 01:25:07,687
No one says no to me!

1137
01:25:12,984 --> 01:25:18,906
I think the transitions Sam uses
are somewhat dated...

1138
01:25:19,115 --> 01:25:23,953
