1195
01:29:41,335 --> 01:29:47,216
They painted out a lot of detail that
we'd add back in later with lighting.

1196
01:29:47,424 --> 01:29:50,219
Also, paint the edges
so we could tile...

1197
01:29:50,427 --> 01:29:54,640
...and reuse some of that photography
to extend buildings.

1198
01:29:54,848 --> 01:29:59,228
Talk about the tiles. That's an
important thing that we used.

1199
01:29:59,478 --> 01:30:03,607
- The tiles in terms of...
- Just how we did it.

1200
01:30:04,900 --> 01:30:08,779
We started out making
this whole building system.

1201
01:30:08,988 --> 01:30:13,409
We knew we would have complex
scenes that had a lot of geometry.

1202
01:30:13,659 --> 01:30:16,745
We made our buildings
as building blocks.

1203
01:30:16,996 --> 01:30:21,792
We used a system that Steve LeVietes
created in Houdini software...

1204
01:30:21,959 --> 01:30:27,590
...to easily instance pieces
and assemble them all together.

1205
01:30:28,215 --> 01:30:32,094
Also there was a notion that
when we took these photos...

1206
01:30:32,303 --> 01:30:34,847
...they had to seam up on the edges.

1207
01:30:35,014 --> 01:30:39,852
If you look at real buildings,
there's lots of variation in color...

1208
01:30:40,060 --> 01:30:43,105
...and lighting across
these buildings.

1209
01:30:43,314 --> 01:30:48,110
Our texture painters had to balance
those out of the textures...

1210
01:30:48,319 --> 01:30:53,616
...make them so they could seam up
together and work generically.

1211
01:30:53,824 --> 01:30:58,662
The beautiful thing about the
tiles is, you get this hemisphere...

1212
01:30:58,912 --> 01:31:01,165
...which functions as a plate.

1213
01:31:01,415 --> 01:31:06,754
But a normal plate, you've gotta work
within what the camera has shot.

1214
01:31:06,962 --> 01:31:11,342
When you have this hemisphere
of tiles stitched together...

1215
01:31:11,592 --> 01:31:14,470
...you can move
the camera all around...

1216
01:31:14,720 --> 01:31:19,391
...and create your own camera move
within this background.

1217
01:31:19,642 --> 01:31:22,186
Our pan and tile system...

1218
01:31:22,394 --> 01:31:27,399
...which was another technique we used
to put behind our CG buildings.

1219
01:31:27,608 --> 01:31:32,988
The camera sits in one place.
You take a shot and then tilt up.

1220
01:31:33,155 --> 01:31:37,117
Take one to the right and left,
until you have these...

1221
01:31:37,284 --> 01:31:43,666
...photos that define or capture
the panorama before you.

1222
01:31:43,916 --> 01:31:49,755
If you look at David Hockney's art,
you see some of this kind of tiling.

1223
01:31:50,005 --> 01:31:54,718
We did it in a much more precise
fashion, but far less artistic.

1224
01:31:54,927 --> 01:31:59,139
It's a lot of single images
which are combined together...

1225
01:31:59,390 --> 01:32:02,893
...to create a much larger image
at high resolution.

1226
01:32:03,143 --> 01:32:08,524
That allows you to move in closer
and further away and to pan...

1227
01:32:08,691 --> 01:32:15,155
...and move up and down
on this big domed projection.

1228
01:32:15,364 --> 01:32:20,619
It's a technique that's been
getting more and more...

1229
01:32:20,869 --> 01:32:24,123
...in use over the last couple
of years.

1230
01:32:24,331 --> 01:32:29,002
Many years ago, you'd have
to assemble it in 3-D and render out.

1231
01:32:29,253 --> 01:32:32,464
Nowadays, at Imageworks,
we've got a system...

1232
01:32:32,715 --> 01:32:39,346
...where we do it in our last
compositing stage so it's much faster.

1233
01:32:42,850 --> 01:32:48,564
One of the interesting things about
visual effects in movies is that...

1234
01:32:48,772 --> 01:32:55,195
...you start out with scripts that have
more stuff than you can afford to do.

1235
01:32:55,404 --> 01:33:00,409
Using resource as a definition
of time and money.

1236
01:33:00,617 --> 01:33:05,330
You always have twice the material
as you have the resource to do.

1237
01:33:05,497 --> 01:33:09,543
Throughout the creation of the film,
you have to go back...

1238
01:33:09,710 --> 01:33:15,048
...and constantly be on top of deciding
where you'll put the resource.

1239
01:33:15,299 --> 01:33:21,472
We knew we had to create a virtual
version of the Spider-Man character...

1240
01:33:21,638 --> 01:33:24,224
...a virtual version of the Goblin...

1241
01:33:24,391 --> 01:33:27,895
...and a virtual version of
portions of New York...

1242
01:33:28,061 --> 01:33:32,524
...to allow us to do the kinds of
camera moves that we wanted...

1243
01:33:32,733 --> 01:33:38,530
...because they weren't allowing
anybody to swing through the streets.

1244
01:33:38,697 --> 01:33:42,993
So those were our primary
allocations of resource.

1245
01:33:43,202 --> 01:33:48,457
Then as the script developed,
as we worked on the movie...

1246
01:33:48,707 --> 01:33:51,168
...the story became clearer to us.

1247
01:33:51,418 --> 01:33:56,965
We then had to re-evaluate where we
were putting our efforts or resource.

1248
01:33:57,216 --> 01:34:02,721
And one of the things that was...
We also knew we had to do the web.

1249
01:34:02,930 --> 01:34:06,350
The web was a component
of resource allocation.

1250
01:34:06,600 --> 01:34:09,561
But as we continued
through the process...

1251
01:34:09,728 --> 01:34:13,732
...we had to re-evaluate
what was being put into the film.

1252
01:34:13,899 --> 01:34:17,986
We'd get new sequences they
wanted to make a story point.

1253
01:34:18,195 --> 01:34:24,243
Then that sequence would be evaluated,
