did for us is...

1357
01:42:11,960 --> 01:42:17,215
...when you've a sequence where points
of view aren't on the same level...

1358
01:42:17,382 --> 01:42:22,220
...you have to establish the camera's
angle relative to the live action.

1359
01:42:22,429 --> 01:42:25,140
Pre-visualization allowed us to say:

1360
01:42:25,348 --> 01:42:31,438
The camera needs to be 40 feet below
the subject on a 15 millimeter lens.

1361
01:42:31,688 --> 01:42:37,485
Those kinds of details allowed us to
photograph our characters...

1362
01:42:37,652 --> 01:42:41,072
...in some cases,
against green screen...

1363
01:42:41,281 --> 01:42:47,829
...then put them into a photography
of the real bridge or a CGI bridge.

1364
01:42:48,038 --> 01:42:50,957
Ken Hahn is the CG
supervisor of this...

1365
01:42:51,124 --> 01:42:56,796
...and did a great job pulling together
all the green screen and CG elements...

1366
01:42:57,005 --> 01:43:01,718
...and putting up with listening
to me talk about the black levels...

1367
01:43:01,926 --> 01:43:05,388
...and different variations
across the images.

1368
01:43:05,805 --> 01:43:12,020
This is a difficult area, to keep the
character doing the same thing...

1369
01:43:12,187 --> 01:43:18,026
...all the time so there's a continuity
of what he does in the physical world.

1370
01:43:18,234 --> 01:43:22,614
You have a temptation to make
the character do something human...

1371
01:43:22,822 --> 01:43:26,076
...and you can't
let yourself fall into that.

1372
01:43:26,326 --> 01:43:32,332
Just like before when he was shooting
web and going through the bridge.

1373
01:43:32,540 --> 01:43:37,337
He comes up, flies over the top
and I had him landing so hard...

1374
01:43:37,504 --> 01:43:40,423
...in this big follow through.

1375
01:43:40,632 --> 01:43:44,803
Sam said, "He can't do that."
I said, "He has to do that."

1376
01:43:45,011 --> 01:43:51,476
I thought about it and he was right.
He's not a person, he's Spider-Man.

1377
01:43:58,566 --> 01:44:02,237
As opposed to this,
which a person could easily do.

1378
01:44:05,657 --> 01:44:08,827
Lots of pieces went
into this sequence.

1379
01:44:09,035 --> 01:44:15,083
The toughest part is you're working
with a large set piece, this bridge.

1380
01:44:15,333 --> 01:44:21,756
You get close to the characters, it's
hard to see the bridge and vice versa.

1381
01:44:21,965 --> 01:44:28,638
So this was a real tour de force
of editing and design of sequence...

1382
01:44:28,847 --> 01:44:33,393
...to integrate the pieces so you
had a sense of the environment...

1383
01:44:33,601 --> 01:44:39,858
...but were still close enough to the
characters to read their emotions.

1384
01:44:42,777 --> 01:44:48,116
It was interesting to just set up all
the lighting of our virtual sets...

1385
01:44:48,324 --> 01:44:52,662
...and matched pieces. Sometimes
it worked, sometimes it didn't.

1386
01:44:52,871 --> 01:44:59,252
We just dialed in different fall offs
and bright and dark areas for shots.

1387
01:44:59,544 --> 01:45:01,337
Spider-Man, watch out!

1388
01:45:14,058 --> 01:45:19,147
Interesting thing about this,
this is our "hulking ruin" sequence.

1389
01:45:19,355 --> 01:45:23,067
Spider-Man gets pretty beat up
in this sequence.

1390
01:45:23,318 --> 01:45:28,573
We made a full CG version
of Spider-Man completely beat up.

1391
01:45:28,781 --> 01:45:31,409
One of our guys
painted beautiful maps.

1392
01:45:31,659 --> 01:45:35,163
It's this pristine CG model
that looks fabulous.

1393
01:45:35,371 --> 01:45:40,168
And by the end of the cut that
they made, it was no longer in there.

1394
01:45:40,335 --> 01:45:44,380
I hope in the sequel, there's
an area where he's beat up...

1395
01:45:44,589 --> 01:45:49,719
...pretty similarly to this so we can
use that model. I'm sure we won't.

1396
01:45:50,720 --> 01:45:54,974
That was the shot that,
because of the rating system...

1397
01:45:55,183 --> 01:45:58,478
He had a mouthful of blood
spewing out...

1398
01:45:58,686 --> 01:46:03,399
...and to get the rating down
to PG-13, we had to turn that blood...

1399
01:46:03,608 --> 01:46:06,444
...from red to clear to be spit.

1400
01:46:06,694 --> 01:46:13,076
We had to take out a bit so it didn't
look like he was spewing a fountain.

1401
01:46:13,910 --> 01:46:17,121
This was an interesting solution
with the web.

1402
01:46:17,330 --> 01:46:19,999
This is of course a new kind of web...

1403
01:46:20,250 --> 01:46:26,005
...but also had to look like the real
web because it was already shot.

1404
01:46:28,091 --> 01:46:31,761
Todd Boyce spent a lot of time
weaving that pattern...

1405
01:46:31,928 --> 01:46:35,598
...making it match the next shot.

1406
01:46:39,686 --> 01:46:44,983
This sequence really got out down.
At one point, it went on for days.

1407
01:46:45,191 --> 01:46:48,152
The thing that happens
is these sequences...

1408
01:46:48,403 --> 01:46:54,158
...end up being distillations
of much, much larger vintages.

1409
01:46:54,367 --> 01:46:57,537
The Razorbats used to be
in this sequence.

1410
01:46:57,787 --> 01:47:02,584
There were Razorbats and even another
kind of thing at some point.

1411
01:47:02,792 --> 01:47:07,505
In this sequence, there were flocks
of them all over the place.

1412
01:47:09,591 --> 01:47:12,510
But again,
I think that the distillation...

1413
01:47:12,677 --> 01:47:16,514
...really focuses on the
development of the characters.

1414
01:47:16,681 --> 01:47:21,060
That's the saving grace of this
movie. You pay more attention...

1415
01:47:21,227 --> 01:47:25,231
...to the people involved
than you do to the...

1416
01:47:25,398 --> 01:47:28,610
- Action.
- Action, yeah.

1417
01:47:31,112 --> 01:47:36,826
This is definitely an homage to
some of Sam's earlier movies.

1418
01:47:36,993 --> 01:47:39,662
<i>Army</i> of Darkness or whatever.

1419
01:47:48,630 --> 01:47:51,257
A lot of speed up on this thing.

1420
01:47:53,593 --> 01:47:55,511
Did that wall move or no?

1421
01:47:57,597 --> 01:48:01,267
- Can't give away all the secrets.
- I'm sorry.

1422
01:48:04,187 --> 01:48:07,774
Again the spider sense
comes into play here.

1423
01:48:07,940 --> 01:48:13,988
The spider sense thing was a huge
combination of many elements.

1424
01:48:14,155 --> 01:48:18,284
It's a beautiful digital blade
that comes out of this.

1425
01:48:20,995 --> 01:48:23,539
It comes out of the glider.

1426
01:48:25,458 --> 01:48:28,753
It's photography
done on the set, paintwork...

1427
01:48:28,920 --> 01:48:32,090
...some CG components
that were generated...

1428
01:48:32,256 --> 01:48:38,137
...in three dimensions and painted and
added. The glider is a virtual...

1429
01:48:38,304 --> 01:48:41,808
...version of the glider,
a CGI version...

1430
01:48:41,974 --> 01:48:44,936
...and that's combined with our...

1431
01:48:45,520 --> 01:48:49,357
...actually live actor
in the foreground.

1432
01:48:49,524 --> 01:48:50,942
Give me your hand.

1433
01:48:51,234 --> 01:48:55,988
For the spider sense shot coming up,
Dan Kramer did a great job...

1434
01:48:56,155 --> 01:49:00,034
...because we shot different ideas,
motion control...

1435
01:49:00,201 --> 01:49:05,415
...and the end result ended up being
a combination of some of those ideas.

1436
01:49:05,581 --> 01:49:10,294
So we had to piece together
different photography in.

1437
01:49:11,754 --> 01:49:13,214
Godspeed, Spider-Man.

1438
01:49:15,133 --> 01:49:16,634
That shot right there.

1439
01:49:28,813 --> 01:49:33,359
We also, actually, had to try
to give a character to the glider...

1440
01:49:33,526 --> 01:49:38,072
...to have it and a certain feeling,
as silly as that may sound.

1441
01:49:38,239 --> 01:49:43,327
Well, it's back to
your faithful servant, the glider...

1442
01:49:43,494 --> 01:49:48,374
...hanging out,
waiting to take care...

1443
01:49:48,541 --> 01:49:49,834
...of the threat.

1444
01:49:50,001 --> 01:49:55,590
And of course that sequence was cut
down to get into the PG-13 rating.

1445
01:49:55,757 --> 01:49:59,385
Some of our work was
cut out of there as well.

1446
01:50:06,350 --> 01:50:11,230
I'm sure in the director's cut, the
R-rated version, that'll show up.

1447
01:50:11,397 --> 01:50:12,982
What have you done?!

1448
01:50:18,988 --> 01:50:23,701
A lot of these shots have to be
leading towards sequels to come.

1449
01:50:23,868 --> 01:50:26,829
Setting up some of the situations.

1450
01:50:30,666 --> 01:50:34,003
So this is the set-up
before the final shot...

1451
01:50:34,170 --> 01:50:38,007
...in which Sam had a small request...

1452
01:50:38,174 --> 01:50:42,345
...that the animation
in this last shot...

1453
01:50:42,512 --> 01:50:45,431
...be more incredible,
more astounding.

1454
01:50:45,598 --> 01:50:51,145
The all time, best animated shot in
history. That was all he asked for.

1455
01:50:51,312 --> 01:50:57,735
We went away and tried to do that.
This went through many generations.

1456
01:50:58,319 --> 01:51:01,614
But it was interesting to see...

1457
01:51:01,823 --> 01:51:06,118
...as we got down I think John
has said before, what is it?

1458
01:51:06,285 --> 01:51:10,957
Ninety percent of your time you
spend getting ready for the shot...

1459
01:51:11,123 --> 01:51:16,045
...and 10 percent getting it done.

1460
01:51:19,131 --> 01:51:22,260
All the camera moves
and the animation.

1461
01:51:22,468 --> 01:51:25,763
There were minute adjustments
on these things.

1462
01:51:25,930 --> 01:51:30,059
One frame of a change
of a move where the camera...

1463
01:51:30,226 --> 01:51:33,062
...would come close to a
building or move.

1464
01:51:33,229 --> 01:51:38,401
It really got down to a beautiful shot
that I think is well remembered...

1465
01:51:38,568 --> 01:51:41,320
...in great animation
by Peter Giliberti.

1466
01:51:41,487 --> 01:51:45,241
Lighting and compositing-wise
it came down to the wire.

1467
01:51:45,408 --> 01:51:50,288
Like, our artists Marc Rienzo,
Jeff Stern, Dan Abrams...

1468
01:51:50,454 --> 01:51:54,375
...Laurence, Dan Eaton
all these guys in the last week...

1469
01:51:54,542 --> 01:51:58,337
...working around the clock,
sleeping under their desks.

1470
01:51:58,504 --> 01:52:02,383
It's funny, the president
of our company, Tim Sarnoff...

1471
01:52:02,550 --> 01:52:06,971
...had to come and force these guys
to go home and walk them out.

1472
01:52:07,138 --> 01:52:10,766
We had people drive them home
so they wouldn't crash.

1473
01:52:10,933 --> 01:52:14,520
That's how dedicated
they were to this last shot.

1474
01:52:14,687 --> 01:52:17,815
It took about seven months
for this last shot.

1475
01:52:17,982 --> 01:52:20,484
When you watch this shot...

1476
01:52:20,651 --> 01:52:26,991
...I mean, if you've seen the movie in
a theatre where it's on a big screen...

1477
01:52:27,158 --> 01:52:32,997
...it actually succeeds in getting you
to sort of be physically involved...

1478
01:52:33,164 --> 01:52:38,669
...in swinging through the city.
In terms of a storytelling component...

1479
01:52:38,836 --> 01:52:43,507
...it gives you a sense of what
it's like to be Spider-Man.

1480
01:52:43,674 --> 01:52:48,012
Not the irony where he has
to deny the woman of his dreams...

1481
01:52:48,179 --> 01:52:51,974
...but where you understand
why he goes forward.

1482
01:52:52,141 --> 01:52:56,604
Why he sees some
kind of real future...

1483
01:52:56,771 --> 01:53:01,567
...in the business of being responsible
for this power he wields.

1484
01:53:01,734 --> 01:53:05,112
It comes along
with some great fun too.

1485
01:53:05,279 --> 01:53:09,200
And I think that this shot
embodies all of those things.

1486
01:53:09,408 --> 01:53:15,039
It embodies the best of the work
of the visual effects in the movie.

1487
01:53:16,874 --> 01:53:18,793
I love you so much, Peter.

1488
01:53:39,522 --> 01:53:44,276
<i>All I wanted was to tell her
how much I loved her.</i>

1489
01:53:44,443 --> 01:53:46,362
I can't...

1490
01:53:48,489 --> 01:53:50,032
You can't what?

1491
01:53:51,158 --> 01:53:52,618
Tell you...

1492
01:53:54,328 --> 01:53:58,666
...everything.
I mean, there's so much to tell.

1493
01:53:59,750 --> 01:54:03,671
Yeah. There's so much to tell.

1494
01:54:04,588 --> 01:54:06,549
I want you to know...

1495
01:54:06,966 --> 01:54:09,635
...that I will always be there
for you.

1496
01:54:09,844 --> 01:54:13,806
I will always be there
to take care of you.

1497
01:54:14,807 --> 01:54:16,809
I promise you that.

1498
01:54:20,104 --> 01:54:22,398
I will always be your friend.

1499
01:54:25,317 --> 01:54:27,194
Only a friend...

1500
01:54:28,070 --> 01:54:29,613
...Peter Parker?

1501
01:54:31,782 --> 01:54:34,618
That's all I have to give.

1502
01:55:00,978 --> 01:55:03,647
<i>Whatever life holds in store for</i> me...

1503
01:55:03,814 --> 01:55:06,692
<i>...I will never forget these words:</i>

1504
01:55:06,901 --> 01:55:11,947
<i>"With great power
comes great responsibility."</i>

1505
01:55:12,114 --> 01:55:16,327
In the performance of the character,
in the beginning...

1506
01:55:16,494 --> 01:55:21,707
...he's not sure what move to make,
where to shoot his web...

1507
01:55:21,874 --> 01:55:26,087
...how to move around it.
And through the film he develops.

1508
01:55:26,253 --> 01:55:31,008
Whereas in this shot, you feel
that he knows where he's going...

1509
01:55:31,175 --> 01:55:36,680
...and exactly what he's doing and
he's in control of his movement.

1510
01:55:40,309 --> 01:55:46,857
I think a lot of the photography ended
up helping us out in the last shot.

1511
01:55:47,024 --> 01:55:52,655
The photography that we got on that
Sunday in downtown L.A. swinging...

1512
01:55:52,822 --> 01:55:56,033
...through the cars
and everything built off of that.

1513
01:55:56,200 --> 01:56:01,080
And that stuff you got in New York
for the tiles. The sort of...

1514
01:56:01,247 --> 01:56:05,626
...golden-hour looking tiles that we
processed and pushed more.

1515
01:56:06,293 --> 01:56:12,383
That sort of grounded it and gave us a
base to build our virtual environment.

1516
01:56:15,803 --> 01:56:21,267
Also we had good success
with finishing the buildings off...

1517
01:56:21,433 --> 01:56:25,980
...and figuring out how to use them
in the lighting...

1518
01:56:26,147 --> 01:56:31,777
...environment to make them feel
more real. So when you...

1519
01:56:32,236 --> 01:56:35,865
...get to the point of watching...

1520
01:56:36,031 --> 01:56:39,702
...what he's doing and what's
happening around him...

1521
01:56:39,910 --> 01:56:41,704
...it's very spectacular.

1522
01:56:41,871 --> 01:56:44,790
The composition,
the choice of buildings...

1523
01:56:44,957 --> 01:56:49,336
...the color compositing.
Even if it were something that were...

1524
01:56:49,503 --> 01:56:53,382
...done for real and wasn't put
together as elements...

1525
01:56:53,549 --> 01:56:58,470
...it would be
a very successful shot.

